TY  - JOUR
T1  - When Plans Change: Examining How People Evaluate Timing Changes in Work Organizations
AU  - Blount, Sally
AU  - Janicik, Gregory A.
Y1  - 2001/10/01
PY  - 2001
DA  - 2001/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2001.5393892
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2001.5393892
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 566
EP  - 585
VL  - 26
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We examine the dynamics of temporal responsiveness?the ability of organizational actors to adapt the timing of their activities to unanticipated events. We review a broad body of psychological, economic, sociological, anthropological, and organizational research to introduce a reference point model of how people perceive and evaluate time in organizations. We then analyze how actors evaluate timing changes (changes from existing organizational schedules, routines, expectations, and plans).
AB  - We examine the dynamics of temporal responsiveness?the ability of organizational actors to adapt the timing of their activities to unanticipated events. We review a broad body of psychological, economic, sociological, anthropological, and organizational research to introduce a reference point model of how people perceive and evaluate time in organizations. We then analyze how actors evaluate timing changes (changes from existing organizational schedules, routines, expectations, and plans).
